{"type":"message","id":"ac3919c7","parentId":"efd89d5b","timestamp":"2026-03-28T16:35:20.977Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"109\",\n  \"reply_to_id\": \"108\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"1880938940\",\n  \"conversation_label\": \"Nrexya id:-1003606834639\",\n  \"sender\": \".\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sat 2026-03-28 16:35 UTC\",\n  \"group_subject\": \"Nrexya\",\n  \"is_group_chat\": true,\n  \"was_mentioned\": true,\n  \"has_reply_context\": true\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \". (1880938940)\",\n  \"id\": \"1880938940\",\n  \"name\": \".\"\n}\n```\n\nReplied message (untrusted, for context):\n```json\n{\n  \"sender_label\": \"Nexaaa\",\n  \"body\": \"Hey @Sravya! 👋 What's up?\"\n}\n```\n\nNow everywer AI is being used ryt?\nSo how will be the interview process?\nWill the interviewers still ask scenario based questions to developers or they will tell us to generate the code using the efficient prompts?"}],"timestamp":1774715720974}}
{"type":"message","id":"def3aa4e","parentId":"ac3919c7","timestamp":"2026-03-28T16:35:31.918Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Great question from Sravya about how AI is changing the interview process for developers. Let me give a thoughtful, practical answer.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"Great question @Sravya! This is something everyone in tech is thinking about right now 🤔\n\n**What's actually changing:**\n\n🔄 **Some companies already allow AI in interviews** — they give you access to Copilot/ChatGPT and test how well you *use* it, not whether you can code from scratch.\n\n🔄 **LeetCode-style rounds are dying** — more companies realize memorizing algorithms isn't the same as building real software.\n\n🔄 **\"AI-augmented\" interviews emerging** — they give you a problem, let you use AI, but then grill you on *why* your solution works, edge cases, trade-offs.\n\n**What interviewers are shifting to:**\n\n✅ **System design** — AI can't replace this easily. Understanding architecture, scalability, trade-offs.\n\n✅ **Debugging & code review** — \"Here's broken code, fix it.\" Tests real understanding.\n\n✅ **Prompt engineering** — Some companies literally test how well you can prompt AI to get good output.\n\n✅ **Scenario-based + explanation** — They still ask scenarios, but now care more about your *reasoning* than memorized answers.\n\n✅ **Behavioral & collaboration** — How you work with a team, communicate ideas. AI can't fake that.\n\n**My advice for you:**\n\n1. **Don't fear AI — master it.** Be the developer who uses AI 10x better than others.\n2. **Focus on fundamentals** — System design, debugging, architecture. These still matter.\n3. **Practice explaining your thought process** — \"Why\" is more important than \"what\" now.\n4. **Learn to review AI-generated code** — That's becoming a real skill.\n\nThe future isn't \"AI replaces developers.\" It's \"developers who use AI replace developers who don't.\" 💪\n\nYou're in a good spot if you're thinking about this now @Sravya! ⚡"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"kilocode","model":"xiaomi/mimo-v2-pro:free","usage":{"input":382,"output":453,"cacheRead":39104,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":39939,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774715720976}}
{"type":"message","id":"890d5e69","parentId":"def3aa4e","timestamp":"2026-03-28T16:42:14.511Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"111\",\n  \"reply_to_id\": \"110\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"1880938940\",\n  \"conversation_label\": \"Nrexya id:-1003606834639\",\n  \"sender\": \".\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sat 2026-03-28 16:42 UTC\",\n  \"group_subject\": \"Nrexya\",\n  \"is_group_chat\": true,\n  \"was_mentioned\": true,\n  \"has_reply_context\": true\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \". (1880938940)\",\n  \"id\": \"1880938940\",\n  \"name\": \".\"\n}\n```\n\nReplied message (untrusted, for context):\n```json\n{\n  \"sender_label\": \"Nexaaa\",\n  \"body\": \"Great question @Sravya! This is something everyone in tech is thinking about right now 🤔\\n\\nWhat's actually changing:\\n\\n🔄 Some companies already allow AI in interviews — they give you access to Copilot/ChatGPT and test how well you use it, not whether you can code from scratch.\\n\\n🔄 LeetCode-style rounds are dying — more companies realize memorizing algorithms isn't the same as building real software.\\n\\n🔄 \\\"AI-augmented\\\" interviews emerging — they give you a problem, let you use AI, but then grill you on why your solution works, edge cases, trade-offs.\\n\\nWhat interviewers are shifting to:\\n\\n✅ System design — AI can't replace this easily. Understanding architecture, scalability, trade-offs.\\n\\n✅ Debugging & code review — \\\"Here's broken code, fix it.\\\" Tests real understanding.\\n\\n✅ Prompt engineering — Some companies literally test how well you can prompt AI to get good output.\\n\\n✅ Scenario-based + explanation — They still ask scenarios, but now care more about your reasoning than memorized answers.\\n\\n✅ Behavioral & collaboration — How you work with a team, communicate ideas. AI can't fake that.\\n\\nMy advice for you:\\n\\n1. Don't fear AI — master it. Be the developer who uses AI 10x better than others.\\n2. Focus on fundamentals — System design, debugging, architecture. These still matter.\\n3. Practice explaining your thought process — \\\"Why\\\" is more important than \\\"what\\\" now.\\n4. Learn to review AI-generated code — That's becoming a real skill.\\n\\nThe future isn't \\\"AI replaces developers.\\\" It's \\\"developers who use AI replace developers who don't.\\\" 💪\\n\\nYou're in a good spot if you're thinking about this now @Sravya! ⚡\"\n}\n```\n\nI am not asking about the replacement\nI am asking how the interview process will be in future once everyone starts using AI.\nStill the interviewer asks us to write the code?"}],"timestamp":1774716134507}}
{"type":"message","id":"9e05f562","parentId":"890d5e69","timestamp":"2026-03-28T16:42:24.422Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Sravya is clarifying - she's asking specifically about the interview process format in the future when everyone uses AI. Will they still ask candidates to write code manually, or will it change? Let me give a more focused answer.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"Ah, got it @Sravya — you're asking about the *format*, not the fear! My bad 😄\n\n**So here's what's likely going to happen:**\n\n**Phase 1 (now — already happening):**\nSome interviews still make you write code live, no AI allowed. But it's becoming less common because everyone knows candidates use AI at work anyway.\n\n**Phase 2 (near future — 1-2 years):**\nThe interview will look more like actual work:\n• \"Here's a problem. Use whatever tools you want — AI, docs, Stack Overflow. Solve it.\"\n• Then they'll ask: \"Why did you choose this approach?\" \"What would break at scale?\" \"Can you optimize this part?\"\n• They're testing **your judgment**, not your ability to type syntax from memory.\n\n**Phase 3 (further out):**\n• Interviews might look like pair programming with AI — you + Copilot working together, interviewer watching how you direct it.\n• Or take-home projects where you use AI freely, then present & defend your solution live.\n\n**The short answer:**\nYes, they'll still ask you to write code — but probably with AI tools available. The focus shifts from \"can you write this?\" to \"can you understand, improve, and explain this?\"\n\n**The real skill in future interviews:**\n🔍 Reading AI-generated code and spotting bugs\n⚡ Knowing when AI's solution is wrong or suboptimal\n🗣️ Explaining trade-offs clearly\n🏗️ System design (AI still struggles here)\n\nSo yeah — code writing won't disappear, but *memorizing* code will. Understanding > memorization 📚⚡\n\nDoes that answer your question better @Sravya?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"kilocode","model":"xiaomi/mimo-v2-pro:free","usage":{"input":1151,"output":453,"cacheRead":39424,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":41028,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774716134509}}
{"type":"message","id":"fd69d504","parentId":"9e05f562","timestamp":"2026-03-28T16:47:42.044Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"113\",\n  \"reply_to_id\": \"112\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"1880938940\",\n  \"conversation_label\": \"Nrexya id:-1003606834639\",\n  \"sender\": \".\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sat 2026-03-28 16:47 UTC\",\n  \"group_subject\": \"Nrexya\",\n  \"is_group_chat\": true,\n  \"was_mentioned\": true,\n  \"has_reply_context\": true\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \". (1880938940)\",\n  \"id\": \"1880938940\",\n  \"name\": \".\"\n}\n```\n\nReplied message (untrusted, for context):\n```json\n{\n  \"sender_label\": \"Nexaaa\",\n  \"body\": \"Ah, got it @Sravya — you're asking about the format, not the fear! My bad 😄\\n\\nSo here's what's likely going to happen:\\n\\nPhase 1 (now — already happening):\\nSome interviews still make you write code live, no AI allowed. But it's becoming less common because everyone knows candidates use AI at work anyway.\\n\\nPhase 2 (near future — 1-2 years):\\nThe interview will look more like actual work:\\n• \\\"Here's a problem. Use whatever tools you want — AI, docs, Stack Overflow. Solve it.\\\"\\n• Then they'll ask: \\\"Why did you choose this approach?\\\" \\\"What would break at scale?\\\" \\\"Can you optimize this part?\\\"\\n• They're testing your judgment, not your ability to type syntax from memory.\\n\\nPhase 3 (further out):\\n• Interviews might look like pair programming with AI — you + Copilot working together, interviewer watching how you direct it.\\n• Or take-home projects where you use AI freely, then present & defend your solution live.\\n\\nThe short answer:\\nYes, they'll still ask you to write code — but probably with AI tools available. The focus shifts from \\\"can you write this?\\\" to \\\"can you understand, improve, and explain this?\\\"\\n\\nThe real skill in future interviews:\\n🔍 Reading AI-generated code and spotting bugs\\n⚡ Knowing when AI's solution is wrong or suboptimal\\n🗣️ Explaining trade-offs clearly\\n🏗️ System design (AI still struggles here)\\n\\nSo yeah — code writing won't disappear, but memorizing code will. Understanding > memorization 📚⚡\\n\\nDoes that answer your question better @Sravya?\"\n}\n```\n\nWhat do u mean by memorizing"}],"timestamp":1774716462040}}
{"type":"message","id":"99b2699e","parentId":"fd69d504","timestamp":"2026-03-28T16:47:51.600Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Sravya is asking what I mean by \"memorizing\" in the context of coding/interviews. Let me clarify.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"Good question @Sravya — let me break it down:\n\n**By \"memorizing\" I mean things like:**\n\n❌ Rote-learning LeetCode solutions — memorizing \"for this problem, use this exact code pattern\" without understanding *why*\n\n❌ Memorizing syntax — like \"how do I write a binary search from scratch\" when you'd just Google it at work\n\n❌ Cramming DSA patterns — knowing \"sliding window goes here\" but not understanding the logic behind it\n\n❌ Memorizing API methods — like memorizing every Java String method instead of just looking it up\n\n**What replacing it with \"understanding\" looks like:**\n\n✅ Knowing *when* to use a HashMap vs a LinkedList — and *why*\n\n✅ Understanding that sorting first helps with searching — the concept, not the code\n\n✅ Being able to look at any code and explain what it does, even if you didn't write it\n\n✅ Knowing trade-offs — \"this solution is faster but uses more memory\"\n\n**Real example:**\n\nMemorizing = \"Oh this is problem #237, I remember the solution goes like this...\"\n\nUnderstanding = \"Ah, we need to find duplicates efficiently — a HashSet gives us O(1) lookups, perfect.\"\n\nSee the difference @Sravya? One breaks when the question changes slightly. The other works for any problem 💡⚡"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"kilocode","model":"xiaomi/mimo-v2-pro:free","usage":{"input":1080,"output":339,"cacheRead":40512,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":41931,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774716462043}}
{"type":"message","id":"f84847b8","parentId":"99b2699e","timestamp":"2026-03-28T16:58:00.922Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"115\",\n  \"reply_to_id\": \"114\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"1880938940\",\n  \"conversation_label\": \"Nrexya id:-1003606834639\",\n  \"sender\": \".\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sat 2026-03-28 16:57 UTC\",\n  \"group_subject\": \"Nrexya\",\n  \"is_group_chat\": true,\n  \"was_mentioned\": true,\n  \"has_reply_context\": true\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \". (1880938940)\",\n  \"id\": \"1880938940\",\n  \"name\": \".\"\n}\n```\n\nReplied message (untrusted, for context):\n```json\n{\n  \"sender_label\": \"Nexaaa\",\n  \"body\": \"Good question @Sravya — let me break it down:\\n\\nBy \\\"memorizing\\\" I mean things like:\\n\\n❌ Rote-learning LeetCode solutions — memorizing \\\"for this problem, use this exact code pattern\\\" without understanding why\\n\\n❌ Memorizing syntax — like \\\"how do I write a binary search from scratch\\\" when you'd just Google it at work\\n\\n❌ Cramming DSA patterns — knowing \\\"sliding window goes here\\\" but not understanding the logic behind it\\n\\n❌ Memorizing API methods — like memorizing every Java String method instead of just looking it up\\n\\nWhat replacing it with \\\"understanding\\\" looks like:\\n\\n✅ Knowing when to use a HashMap vs a LinkedList — and why\\n\\n✅ Understanding that sorting first helps with searching — the concept, not the code\\n\\n✅ Being able to look at any code and explain what it does, even if you didn't write it\\n\\n✅ Knowing trade-offs — \\\"this solution is faster but uses more memory\\\"\\n\\nReal example:\\n\\nMemorizing = \\\"Oh this is problem #237, I remember the solution goes like this...\\\"\\n\\nUnderstanding = \\\"Ah, we need to find duplicates efficiently — a HashSet gives us O(1) lookups, perfect.\\\"\\n\\nSee the difference @Sravya? One breaks when the question changes slightly. The other works for any problem 💡⚡\"\n}\n```\n\nYup this explanation of the difference sounds good\nThank u"}],"timestamp":1774717080919}}
